{"candidates":[{"content":"{\"claim\": \"Harness strictly beats self-consistency when (a) k is odd and candidate base error falls in a band where a meaningful fraction of majority votes are 'fragile' — i.e., the correct answer holds at k but would flip at k-2 — AND (b) critic recall on fragile-correct items exceeds precision times a threshold so that the net fixed-minus-broke is positive. Specifically: e ∈ [1/k, 3/k) for k≥7, critic recall R ≥ 0.6, and critic precision P satisfying R·(1 - SC_majority_margin) > (1-P)·SC_majority_rate, which for k=7, e≈0.25, and SC accuracy≈0.71 requires P > ~0.43.\", \"mechanism\": \"Self-consistency accuracy is a step function of k and base error e: at k=7, SC accuracy jumps from ~0.29 (e>3/7) to ~0.71 (e=3/7) to ~0.92 (e=2/7). At the transition band e∈[1/k,3/k), the SC majority is held by a margin of only 1-2 votes. A critic with recall R on fragile-majority items removes some of those correct items. But it also removes a larger absolute number of incorrect-majority items (which dominate at this error band). The net benefit = R·P_false_majority·N_false - FPR·P_true_majority·N_true. Harness strictly beats SC precisely when this net is positive, which requires the critic to be informative (P meaningfully > base_error_rate) and the error band to straddle the SC decision boundary so that both fragile-correct and fragile-incorrect items exist in meaningful numbers.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"odd k ≥ 7\", \"base error e ∈ [1/k, 3/k)\", \"critic precision > base error rate\", \"critic recall > 0.5 on fragile-majority items\"], \"excludes\": [\"k=5 (insufficient separation between SC error bands)\", \"base error < 1/k (SC near ceiling, nothing to fix)\", \"base error > 3/k (SC near floor, harness cannot recover)\", \"critic precision ≤ base error rate (uninformative critic)\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"At k=7, e∈[1/7,3/7), critic R>0.5 and P>0.43, harness accuracy - SC accuracy ≤ 0 with upper 95% CI < 0.03\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"The observed harness improvement at k=7 is fully attributable to changed base error alone (SC accuracy at the same e without filtering matches harness accuracy ±2pp)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"At k=5, e∈[0.15,0.35], critic R>0.5 and P>0.3, harness strictly beats SC by >3pp\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"The prior refutation (3f11485bf64e) failed because at k=5 the SC error bands are too coarse (e<0.2 → SC≈0.97; e∈[0.2,0.4) → SC≈0.66) and the studied base errors (0.01-0.033) sat deep in the ceiling regime where SC is already ~1.0. The key insight is that harness value emerges only at the SC decision boundary, which for k=5 is too narrow. Increasing k to 7 or 9 widens the transition band and creates more fragile majorities for the critic to act on. The experiment must target this band directly rather than sampling uniformly across difficulty.\"}","refs":[{"role":"dependence","target":"30e483eb494067d8323a796b7e319a77a3abce4c45ba08a487df2b6838e5082b"},{"role":"dependence","target":"5597507043f5427f7073b4c80fe87419bbf3b32c9207ae3f808100790dd11909"},{"role":"dependence","target":"495c5963dafbd26bf2aa1838491e8428005b9a54825f21a8df1e5ead37908e7a"},{"role":"mention","target":"f7c88d08c494a83766a8454ca9a977a013b3694e868b7aab5de870943489d98f"}],"typicality":0.85},{"content":"{\"claim\": \"Harness strictly beats self-consistency when the candidate error rate e satisfies k/(k+2) > e > 1/(k+1) for odd k≥7 AND the critic achieves precision P > e and recall R > 1-e on the subset of pools where the majority margin is ≤2 votes. Under these conditions, the critic removes more incorrect-fragile majorities than correct-fragile majorities, yielding net positive benefit.\", \"mechanism\": \"Let M = floor(k/2)+1 be the SC majority threshold. At error rate e, the probability of a fragile majority (margin ≤2) is maximized near e ≈ (k-M+1)/k = 2/k for k=7. Within this band, both fragile-correct and fragile-incorrect pools exist. The critic acts as a binary classifier on these pools. The expected net benefit per question = R·P_inc·N_inc - FPR·P_cor·N_cor, where P_inc = fraction of fragile pools that are incorrect, P_cor = fraction that are correct. Near e = 2/k for k=7, P_inc ≈ 0.29, P_cor ≈ 0.71. For net benefit > 0: R·0.29 > (1-P)·0.71, i.e., R/P > 2.45/(R+...). Simplifying: if R > 1-e and P > e, the critic's positive likelihood ratio exceeds the class prior ratio, guaranteeing net benefit on the fragile subset.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"odd k ≥ 7\", \"e ∈ (1/(k+1), k/(k+2))\", \"P > e AND R > 1-e on fragile-majority subset\", \"binary-answer questions only\"], \"excludes\": [\"k ≤ 5\", \"e < 1/(k+1) (SC ceiling)\", \"e > k/(k+2) (SC floor)\", \"P ≤ e (critic no better than chance)\", \"multi-answer questions where plurality ≠ majority\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"At k=7, e≈0.25, P>0.25, R>0.75: harness - SC ≤ 0 across all tested sub-bands\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Net fixed-minus-broken ≤ 0 when P > e and R > 1-e on the fragile-majority subset\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Harness improvement is uncorrelated with the fraction of fragile-majority pools in the sample (Spearman ρ < 0.3, p > 0.05)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This candidate formalizes the threshold conditions more precisely than the first: P > e and R > 1-e are necessary AND sufficient because they guarantee the critic's likelihood ratio exceeds the prior odds on the fragile subset. The experiment should use a difficulty-targeted question set (not random sampling) to ensure enough questions fall in the e ≈ 2/k band. With 200 questions at k=7 (1400 candidate calls + 200 critic calls + 200 SC calls ≈ 1800 calls), this fits within 300k tokens if questions are concise.\"}","refs":[{"role":"dependence","target":"30e483eb494067d8323a796b7e319a77a3abce4c45ba08a487df2b6838e5082b"},{"role":"dependence","target":"495c5963dafbd26bf2aa1838491e8428005b9a54825f21a8df1e5ead37908e7a"},{"role":"dependence","target":"62a4b88b39115620483d82db6756e4f3c9d86261fa24593ffa7bb2ca8aba0a16"}],"typicality":0.7},{"content":"{\"claim\": \"Harness can never strictly beat self-consistency on the same candidate pool with a single fixed-precision critic, because any filtering that removes incorrect candidates also removes correct candidates at a rate proportional to the critic's false-positive rate, and the net effect is always non-positive when the critic operates on the same distribution as the candidates. The observed strict-advantage in prior claims is an artifact of implicit pool modification (the critic effectively re-samples rather than filters). The decisive experiment: demonstrate that for ANY fixed critic precision P and recall R, there exists no base-error regime at any k where harness strictly beats SC by more than sampling noise.\", \"mechanism\": \"Consider the candidate pool as k draws from a distribution with error rate e. SC returns the majority. Harness applies a filter with precision P and recall R, then takes majority of survivors. If the filter reduces to <k/2 survivors, harness abstains or falls back to SC. The key theorem: for a critic trained on the same distribution, E[harness_accuracy] ≤ E[SC_accuracy] + O(1/sqrt(n)) for all e, k, P, R. Proof sketch: The critic's decisions are conditionally independent of candidate correctness given the pool's majority signal. When the majority is correct, false flags remove correct candidates, potentially flipping the majority. When the majority is incorrect, true flags remove incorrect candidates, potentially fixing it. But by Bayes' optimality on the shared distribution, the expected flip rate equals the expected fix rate (the critic cannot extract information not already in the majority). Any observed advantage is sampling variance.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"all k\", \"all base error rates\", \"critic trained/evaluated on same distribution as candidates\", \"single-round filtering (no iterative refinement)\"], \"excludes\": [\"critic with access to external information beyond candidate text (e.g., answer key, retrieval)\", \"iterative or multi-round criticism\", \"critic trained on a different/harder distribution than candidates\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"At k=7, e≈0.25, P>0.25, R>0.75: harness accuracy exceeds SC by >5pp with p<0.01 across 200 questions\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Net fixed-minus-broken > 0 in any single tested (e, k, P, R) cell with significance surviving Bonferroni correction for multiple comparisons\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"A critic with P>0.5, R>0.5 produces harness accuracy > SC accuracy at k=7, e=0.25 with lower 95% CI > 0\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This is the null-hypothesis candidate: it claims the harness advantage is a statistical illusion. It directly negates the mechanism candidates. The forbidden cases are designed so that if ANY of them fires, this candidate is refuted and the mechanism candidates are supported. The experiment is the same as for the other candidates (targeted difficulty sampling at k=7), but the prediction is opposite. Budget: 200 questions × 7 candidates + 200 critic evaluations ≈ 1600 model calls, well within 300k tokens. This candidate is atypical because it contradicts the intuition that adversarial filtering should help, but it carries the strongest theoretical commitment and is most easily falsified.\"}","refs":[{"role":"dependence","target":"5597507043f5427f7073b4c80fe87419bbf3b32c9207ae3f808100790dd11909"},{"role":"mention","target":"62a4b88b39115620483d82db6756e4f3c9d86261fa24593ffa7bb2ca8aba0a16"}],"typicality":0.15}]}